<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-01-19T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-01-19T13:00:00-05:00" n="673" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d673">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">882.01 Foreign Control/771:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-01-19T19:00:00+01:00">January 19, 1934—7
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received January 19—3:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>15. From Reber. In public session this afternoon Council adopted the
                                Liberian <hi rend="italic">rapport</hi><note n="7" xml:id="d673fn7">For text, see League of Nations, <hi rend="italic">Official
                                        Journal</hi>, 1934, pt. 1, p. 153 (document
                                    C.72.1934.VII).</note> in substantially the terms outlined in
                                Consulate’s telegram 14, January 17, 8 p.m.</p>
                            <pb facs="0892" n="792" xml:id="pg_792"/>
                            <p>Sottile claimed, however, that the reply of his Government did not
                                constitute a refusal. Simon<note n="8" xml:id="d673fn8">Sir John
                                    Simon, British Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs.</note>
                                expressed the hope that the Liberian representative would remind his
                                Government of the unanimous decision of the Council that the report
                                must be accepted as a whole. [Reber.]</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>